\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 MIDI Keyboard Sensivity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Change the sensitivity of the MIDI input, i.e. the relation between keyboard touch and velocity. Values : 0-4:light touch, 5: normal touch, 6-9:heavy touch, 10: constant touch\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script displays smoothly scrolling lyrics in a separate window.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lyrics are imported from a TEXT file (one sentence per line, empty lines are excluded) in the form of media items in a dedicated lyrics track, named "Lyrics" (not case sensitive)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If not existing, this track is automaticaly created.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab By default, the TEXT file browser points in the project directory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab During import, lyrics can be added at the end of the existing lyrics as new items, or can replace the existing ones.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab After import, you can move and resize items to synchronize currently displayed lyrics with the underlying music.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The currently displayed lyric lines depend on the position of the edit or play cursor on the timeline.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab By default, the size of the lyrics window becomes bigger when the project is playing, to easily read the lyrics from your recording position, far from the screen.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab On the contrary, when the project is stopped, the window size is reduced to allow easy editing of the tracks underneath.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can disable this behaviour with the "auto resize" options, if you want.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can also change the fonts sizes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can change the colors of lines, depending on their status (reading, preparing, offline)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can choose how many lines you want to see before of after the current one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can change the position and size of the window in both playing/stopped modes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can change the default duration of a lyric item, and the default duration of the gap between lyric items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab All these choices/options are memorized for the next reaper session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Note that the first track called "Lyrics" is taken into account, so you can have several tracks scalled "Lyrics"; just put the active one in the upper position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To avoid useless cpu work, note that, if you modify the lyric track during playback, the display is not updated. you have to stop and resume playback to refresh the lyrics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use the context menu (mouse right click).\sa180\par}
}

